`crates/ctx-scan/src` is the whole `ctx-scan` binary: a standalone tool that walks an arbitrary directory (git or not), maintains a `.context/` tree of generated summaries via content hashing, and exposes both a CLI and programmatic entry points (`runner::scan_run/check_run/update_run`). Depending on this crate gets you staleness detection with zero model calls (`--check`) and targeted regeneration of only changed files (`--update`), without requiring the scanned tree to be a git repo.

The core coupling runs walker → hash → runner: `walker::walk_dir` produces the scoped file list (via `.ctxignore`, seeded once from `.gitignore`), `hash::compute`/`diff` turn that into a `Staleness` (stale dirs deepest-first, changed files, orphan leaves, missing artifacts), and `runner::regenerate` consumes `Staleness` in that exact order — changed files, then orphans, then stale dirs bottom-up — so rollups see already-regenerated children. Any change to `Staleness`'s field order or `hash::diff`'s ordering guarantee breaks `runner.rs` silently. `cli.rs` and `main.rs` are two dispatch surfaces that must stay in sync manually: adding a mode means wiring both `cli::dispatch` and a `runner::*_run` function, per `lib.rs`'s explicit note.

Each file's role from here: `walker.rs` decides scope, `hash.rs` decides freshness, `runner.rs` orchestrates and is the only place hash sidecars get written, `cli.rs` renders and dispatches, `main.rs` is the process shell (owns fail-open behavior for the stop-hook and the pre-clap `--contract` probe), `contract.rs`/`readme.rs` hold static user-facing text kept in sync with generated docs, `error.rs` unifies error types across all of it.

Invariant spanning the subtree: only `scan_run` and non-fresh `update_run` ever call `hash::store`; `check_run` and a fresh `update_run` never write to disk, and `stop_hook` never invokes the agent at all.

No `intent.md` exists to check against.